We notice immediately that there are also large sections of black tiles. Presumably, these represent sections that are missing or empty or corrupted, and we will need to fill in these sections with the appropriate colored tiles to fill in the pattern that has been established in the rest of the grid. Those black colored sections have been filled in with the exact tiles that satisfy the local repeating pattern, as established by the rest of the input grid. Thus, the hypothesis is the following. However, there will also be some number of large sections of black tiles, of some shape or size, that represent an empty part of the input grid. In order to construct the output grid, we need to effectively fill in these black sections with the appropriate tiles that would continue the repeating pattern, and also copy over the rest of the input grid as is so that all of the black tiles are gone and what remains is a repeating multicolored tile pattern. The exact colors to fill in to the black sections must be figured out by the repeating pattern as established locally nearby and globally in the rest of the input grid.
